values:
&nbsp;So, since I'm single now, maybe I will post on my lj more often? I would kind of like to post a daily NYC observation of some kind. Here's the first one, which is delightful (also x-posted to plans):

Today as I stepped out of my apartment and walked to the subway, I was overwhelmed by the extremely distinctive scent of menstrual blood for a solid block. NYC smells like urine and rotting trash a lot, but menstrual blood is a new one.&nbsp;

Melodee points out that maybe I was just smelling regular blood. Which raises the question, does menstrual blood smell differently than real blood? Is the reason you can smell menstrual blood just that there happens to be a lot of it and you normally wouldn't have that much hanging around? I also wonder, like, does other people's blood smell differently?

Another list of things: 

*&nbsp;Cheers to Becker winning the Primary! Awesome! 

* I successfully completed my Orange Belt test in Kung Fu yesterday. Sensei says I need to focus on my effort and bring out the inner chi of the snake. You know what I say? I need to kick more ass. 

*&nbsp;This weekend I attended two Global Film Initiative movies, in addition to seeing a Brazilian movie called House of Sand. House of Sand just came out on video and I really recommend it. Very surreal and an interesting parable on time, age, and being trapped.&nbsp; 

* I rented the DVD set of punk rockers being interviewed by Tom Snyder on the Tomorrow Show from the Library. He interviews Patti Smith and she's really cute and embarassed, but then talks real seriously about death being transcendental with that great Jersey accent of hers. He also interviews Joan Jett a little, although she's terrified and shy and painfully polite. But really, it's not her&nbsp;fault because Tom Snyder&nbsp;has to be the most awkward and bizarre talk show host of all time. I really don't get it at all. He's like the definition of a square. It's&nbsp;actually kind of reassuring to&nbsp;see rock stars being all quiet and tongue-tied&nbsp;because it shows that they really did need to express their full selves through music because they were too introverted to do it any other way. And Joan Jett&nbsp;also gets points because when she's asked if she's gonna sell out when she's&nbsp;successful and mainstream, she&nbsp;says,&nbsp;"Well a band of all girls will never be mainstream." I also&nbsp;watched the Elvis Costello episode and I don't know what it is about him, but he just always seems like a total prick to me. &nbsp; 

* I'm going to New York City tonight. Plans thus far: see Patti Smith, go to the Brooklyn Museum to see Judy Chicago's Dinner Party, eat a Lobster Roll, hang out with Emily and see her hood. Did I mention seeing Patti Smith? Other possibilities include: Hang out with Vy Ho, other museums, jazz music, Greenwich Village, shopping, sit in on a law class, convert to Judaism.&nbsp;Figure out my future life plans? Decide to leave Salt Lake City? Hmph.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
